article.description: Chasity Melvin had a season-high 25 points and 10 rebounds to help keep the Washington Mystics unbeaten at home with an 87-80 victory over the Connecticut Sun on Sunday night.
article.headline: Melvin's season-high 25 keep Mystics unbeaten at home
article.linkText: Melvin's season-high 25 keep Mystics unbeaten at home
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- A little film session was all Chasity Melvin
needed to get back on track.

Melvin had a season-high 25 points, 10 rebounds and five assists
to help keep the Washington Mystics unbeaten at home with an 87-80
victory over the Connecticut Sun on Sunday night.

"I watched films of the last game we played them and I just
wasn't aggressive enough," Melvin said. "I just wanted to give
the team some good energy because the loss to Detroit (92-86 on
Saturday) was mentally disappointing for us. It's hard to bounce
back from that because we felt like we should have won."

Four Washington (8-5) players scored in double figures as the
Mystics snapped a two-game slide and won their seventh in a row at
home. They also ended the Connecticut's (10-4) three-game winning
streak.

"I hope we're getting to be unbeatable here because the road is
hard," Melvin said. "I'm just real proud of the way we played
tonight. We were playing at home but we were also playing the
number one team."

The victory was the Mystics' first against the Sun in their last
eight meetings.

Nikki Teasley, who scored four points in the final 1:37,
finished with 16 points and five assists. Alana Beard, who has
scored in double figures every game this season, had 15 points and
seven rebounds for Washington. Nakia Sanford added 10 points and
nine rebounds.

The Sun also had four players in double figures, led by Taj
McWilliams-Franklin, Nykesha Sales and former Mystics forward Asjha
Jones, with 15 points apiece. Katie Douglas added 10 points for
Connecticut.

"We dug a hole too deep in the first half," Sales said. "They
were a little more aggressive, more energetic, more wanting the
game than we did. We fought back, but if we gave the least little
bit of effort in the first half it would have been a different
story."

"It was the worst first half that we've ever played," Sun
coach Mike Thibault said.

Sales pulled Connecticut to 79-78 on a jumper with 1:55
remaining, but that was as close as the Sun got down the stretch.
Lindsay Whalen, who scored six points on 2-for-7 shooting, missed
an open layup and a 3-pointer in the final 1:16.

"They got back in the game and we finished the game," Melvin
said. "In the second half we were able to get a little more
aggressive because no one was in foul trouble. Everybody just
played a little better defense."

Washington played without DeLisha Milton-Jones, who is out for
six to eight weeks with a sprained medial collateral ligament in
her left knee.

"When DeLisha went down our roles changed," Melvin said.
"We're still adjusting to new roles. We're definitely going to
keep getting better. We're trying to get to the playoffs so
hopefully whenever she comes back we can finish accomplishing what
we're trying to accomplish this year."
